post_text:
This year we celebrate more than your academic accomplishments, we celebrate your resiliency, and fight to
succeed in the midst of unprecedented times.

We also celebrate our PCSS Parents!

You sailed in uncharted waters, side by side, with your children. You did your best to make this ride as smooth as possible. You are remarkable!!

Teachers and Staff…you went above and beyond!! You are appreciated!!!

As we end this school year, please know that your every effort counted, and it will be remembered for a lifetime.

You are all Champions!!!
Thank everyone for giving your best!!!

PCSSI PTO

post_text:
We are deeply saddened and outraged by the killing of George Floyd at the hands of those who were sworn to protect. It was devastating to watch the video footage of the incident. We are in disbelief of how brutal actions like this can still take place in 2020. We grieve with his family and community.

Racism has no place in our society - today or in the future. We all stand united against bigotry, racism, and inequality.

Together we will battle injustice and make our world a better place for all.

post_text: On February 12th, Ibi Zoboi, Haitian American writer, came to visit the PCSS upper school. During a whole school assembly, not only did she share her immigrant story, but she also encouraged students to share their family stories. Her discussion with students was filled with engagement and moments of learning. She spoke about the history of Haiti. Ibi discussed her young adult novel, American Street. She signed several copies of her books for our ever growing library.

February Break Basketball Clinics

Panther Sports Camp will hold basketball skills clinics for girls at the PCSS Gym, 51 Summer Street in Everett over the February break. The clinics are open to the public and will be run by PCSS Girls Varsity Basketball coach Eric Ferguson. The clinics are open to girls from kindergarten - 8th Graders.

The clinics are being held to raise funds for the PCSS Athletic Department to purchase a new scoreboard for the gym. Each session is $10 and players can attend one or both sessions for their age group.

February 18 - K - 4th Grade - 9:30am - 10:30am

February 18 - 5th -8th Grade - 10:30am - 11:30am

February 19 - K - 4th Grade - 9:30am - 10:30am

February 19 - 5th -8th Grade - 10:30am - 11:30am

Space is limited. Please register in advance.

post_text: At our mid-year middle school award ceremony, we had the opportunity to celebrate the many successes of our students. Students from grades 5 through 8 were recognized for achieving Student of the Month, Character Award, Honor Roll, and High Honors. We are so proud of how hard our students work each and every day, and are thankful to have been able to give those students a night of celebration. We would like to thank all of the students, parents, and teachers who helped make this event a success

post_text: Last week was PCSS Annual Black Out Bullying Week. Each grade level had a seminar tailored to their developmental needs given by the School Adjustment Counselor. The overall message was to be kind and put an end to bullying. In the theme of being kind on Friday the whole school dressed in black to spread anti bullying awareness and donated $2 to the Humane Society International for their Animal Rescue Team's efforts in Australia.

The 5-6th grade boys fell to Prospect Hill 26-25. Every player saw action and played tough defense.

After falling behind by double digits in the first half of the game, the Panthers battled back to take the lead in the second half. PHA would regain the lead in the final minute to win the nailbiter.Marcus T. (10 points) and Aviel L. (6 points) led the way on offense.

Holiday Basketball Skills Clinics for Girls

Panther Sports Camp will hold basketball skills clinics for girls at the PCSS Gym, 51 Summer Street in Everett over the holiday break. The clinics are open to the public and will be run by PCSS Girls Varsity Basketball coach Eric Ferguson. The clinics are open to girls from kindergarten - 8th Graders.

The clinics are being held to raise funds for the PCSS Athletic Department to purchase a new scoreboard for the gym. Each session is $10 and players can attend one or both sessions for their age group.

post_text: Always a pleasure having Richard Haynes visit PCSS. Richard joined UNH’s admissions team as associate director for diversity recruiting in 2005. His service is fueled by his deep belief that all students, regardless of background, race, socio-economic status, ethnicity, religion, gender or gender identity, should have access to higher education. For the last 13 years, he has developed strong relationships between UNH Admissions and counselors and students at high schools across northern New England. And often, he works one-on-one with students to present their most compelling admissions case. He is an inspiring speaker who freely shares his own story of hardship growing up in South Carolina’s low country, and later in Harlem. We look forward to having him back next year.

post_text: Dr. Heather Mattie is an instructor of data science and the executive director of the Health Data Science Master’s program in the Biostatistics department at the Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health. She teaches several courses including Introduction to Data Science, Reproducible Data Science, and Data Science II: Deep Learning. Her research interests include methods for minimizing algorithmic bias, methods for social network data imputation, the estimation and prediction of tie strength in large-scale social networks, and studying the causes and potential pathways of improvement for health disparities. Heather is also highly involved in the diversity and inclusion efforts of the School and teaches and mentors underrepresented minority students each summer as part of the Summer Program in Biostatistics and Computational Biology hosted by the department of Biostatistics. Heather also works as a data scientist for Wellframe, a Boston-based digital health company, working to improve health management targeting efforts. Thank You for speaking to our students Dr. Heather.

post_text: We are excited to announce that we have another great Alum working for us. Welcome back Joe Paone! After graduating from Pioneer Charter School of Science in 2014 Joe went to The University of Massachusetts Amherst where he received a bachelor’s degree in Biochemistry/ Molecular Biology with a double major in Neuroscience. Joe is enrolled in an Prosthetic/Orthotic Master Degree program. At the PCSS High School Joe as an assistant coach for the soccer team, teaches AP Physics/Physics and engineering. We are happy to have him back.

post_text:
Our First Library at PCSS

PCSS I is trying to build its first school library. The Book Drive is focused on bringing in quality books for our students. We have created a wishlist through Amazon for books that we would love to have in our library. We want to make sure that our students have access to a variety of books, whether they be fiction or nonfiction. Books are just one of the many ways to explore the universe so help send our students on the adventure of a lifetime!

"A book is a gift you can open again and again." - Garrison Keillor

Library Wish List: https://www.amazon.com/hz/wishlist/ls/22O1X0SETON81?ref_=wl_share

Please spread the word!!

post_text:
The Pioneer Charter School of Science will offer several sports camps this summer.

BASKETBALL - Weeks of July 29 - August 2 and August 5 - 9. The camp is open to the public and will be run by PCSS Boys Varsity Basketball coach Ryan McGowan. Open to incoming 3rd - 8th Graders.

SOCCER - Week of July 29 - August 2. The camp is open to the public and will be run by PCSS Boys Varsity Soccer coach Phil Signoroni. Open to incoming 3rd - 8th Graders.

VOLLEYBALL - Week of August 5 - August 9. The camp is open to the public and will be run by PCSS Boys and Girls Varsity Volleyball coaches Emilee Greco and Dana Martin. Open to incoming 5th - 8th Graders.

VOLLEYBALL HIGH SCHOOL TRAINING CLINIC - Week of August 5 - August 9. Open to all incoming 9th-12th grade boys and girls.

Panther Sports Camps offers an opportunity for any child to come out, have fun, and participate in activities designed to increase their heart rates and fitness level.

FOR MORE INFORMATION AND TO REGISTER, GO TO:

https://www.familyid.com/pcss-everett-athletic-department/panther-sports-camps-summer-2019

post_text:
Congratulations to the Panther Track team for finishing in 3rd place in MCSAO Middle School Track Championships.

The Panthers were one of 27 middle schools to compete in Thursday's meet at Madison Park High School in Boston. Individual medalists included gold medals by Mak C. in the Boys 100 meter and Juan V. in the Boys 800 meter. Silver was earned by the boys 4x100M Relay team made up of Trey P., Abdel N., Caio C., and Mak C. and Marwa Y. in the Girls 800M. Finishing in third with a Bronze was Zuzu H. in the Girls 1600M. Congratulations to coaches O'Neil and Pelczar and the whole team on a successful season! Go Panthers!

NHS Induction Ceremony

On Thursday, May 16th our National Honor Society chapters inducted 13 new members.

Four main purposes have guided chapters of NHS from the beginning:
1. To create enthusiasm for scholarship.
2. To stimulate a desire to render service.
3. To promote leadership.
4. To develop character in the students of secondary school.

Congratulations!

Check out our album "Dilution LAB" at http://edne.tw/a176583

In Chemistry students conducted a Dilution Lab. Dilution is the process of reducing the concentration of a solution simply by adding more solvent. In this lab, students prepared their concentrated stock solution by dissolving CuCl2 in water. Then, they diluted their stock solutions to the given concentrations by adding a certain amount of water they calculated before.

Second grade went on a field trip to the New England Aquarium!

The students were able to touch stingrays and starfish! They saw other animals such as jellyfish, penguins, sea lions, and sharks! The students watched and IMAX movie called Turtle Odyssey where they learned about the life cycle of a sea turtle and the great adventures it goes on during its life.

BCM Trip

On March 27th the first grade took a trip to the Boston Children's Museum.

We were able to see a special exhibit called: Money Matters. At this exhibit, the students got to role play as community members being both workers and consumers. They were barbers, grocery clerks, cafe workers, and more. We learned a little bit about the importance of spending our money wisely. We had a fun filled day of exploration. Thank you so much to all the chaperones and a special thanks to Ms. Chaffee who worked hard to make this such a great trip. We had a blast!

post_text:
New Zealand Comes to PCSS!
On Wednesday, January 30 the Panthers JV and Varsity Boys Basketball teams hosted games against Rotorua Boys' High School from Rotorua, New Zealand.

Both JV and Varsity games started with the Rotorua teams performing a ceremonial Haka, which is a dance or challenge in Māori culture. It was a wonderful experience for our students and an example of how sport can bring people together from different cultures and parts of the world. The evening concluded with all teams enjoying dinner and gathering together to get to know one another.
